#compdef yorick
# =============================================================================
# yorick — David H. Munro's "interpreted language for numerical
#           analysis and postprocessing" — a 1996-vintage numerical-
#           computing interpreted language developed at Lawrence
#           Livermore National Laboratory (LLNL).  Yorick is a
#           C-like array language similar in spirit to MATLAB and
#           Octave but designed in 1994-1996 for post-processing
#           large fluid-dynamics + plasma-physics simulation results
#           on Cray supercomputers.  Key features:
#             - Array-oriented (vector/matrix operations are
#               primitive — no explicit loops needed for elementwise
#               math)
#             - Built-in X Window graphics (interactive xy-plots,
#               contour plots, mesh plots, cell arrays, with output
#               to binary CGM or PostScript files)
#             - Binary-file I/O package that can read/write floating-
#               point formats foreign to the host machine
#               (essential for heterogeneous Cray-Sun-DEC clusters
#               of 1990s LLNL)
#             - Extensive math library (Bessel functions, gamma,
#               multiple-key sorting, splines, rational-function
#               and least-squares fitting, netCDF I/O)
#             - Embedded subroutine support (C/Fortran compiled
#               packages link into the Yorick interpreter)
#           Yorick was DESIGNED FOR LLNL'S NUCLEAR WEAPONS RESEARCH
#           DATA PROCESSING — fluid simulations of inertial
#           confinement fusion targets produced terabytes of output
#           that needed array-oriented analysis tools.  Yorick is
#           still actively maintained at LLNL as one of the
#           internal scientific scripting languages, also released
#           openly for academic and government use.
#
# Author:  David H. Munro at Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory.
#          Munro is the sole architect; Yorick was released
#          publicly in 1996 (manpage dated 1994-08-30 suggesting
#          development started 1993-1994).  Maintained for 30+
#          years (1994-2026).
# Source:  https://github.com/LLNL/yorick
# CLI:     yorick/std0.c (custom C argv processing using strcmp() to
#                          test argv[1] == "-batch" then loop through
#                          remaining args reading -i file.i pairs)
# Library: Hand-rolled C strcmp-based argv parser
#          (Yorick's argv parser is a custom C loop that doesn't
#           use getopt(3), getopt_long(3), or any library.  It
#           tests the first argument specifically for "-batch" then
#           processes the remaining args as a flat list of source
#           files prefixed with -i flags.  Single-dash long-option
#           convention inherited from 1990s LLNL Fortran/C
#           command-line conventions.)
# License: BSD-3-Clause
# Status:  Active — 84+ stars on LLNL/yorick (relatively low star
#          count for a 30-year-old language reflects its niche
#          scientific-computing audience); continuous development
#          since 1994 by David H. Munro at LLNL.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — 71ST DOCUMENTED LANGUAGE
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents
# its 71ST LANGUAGE — Yorick.  Yorick joins the corpus as a single-
# instance language (Yorick=1) via the canonical `yorick` interpreter
# binary using a hand-rolled C argv parser.  Taxonomy now spans 292
# cross-language CLI library variants across 71 documented languages.
#
# Leaderboard unchanged: Rust=45 / Go=45 / TS-Node=45 (three-way tie
# at 45 preserved from R552).  Yorick=1 (new — 71st language entry).
#
# This is the SECOND documented NATIONAL-LAB / SCIENTIFIC-COMPUTING
# language in the taxonomy (alongside Modelica R529 from Linköping
# University's PELAB).  Yorick is also one of the OLDEST documented
# scientific-computing languages still in active maintenance —
# Yorick predates Python's NumPy (2006) by 12 years and competed
# directly with early IDL (1977), Matlab (1984), and S/R (1976) for
# the LLNL/government-lab numerical-computing niche.
#
# Pattern: 3 leader bumps (R550 termion Rust → R551 tcell Go → R552
# terminal-kit TS-Node completing low-level-terminal-primitives
# triple) followed by 1 NEW LANGUAGE (R553 THIS, Yorick as 71st).
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS YORICK AND WHY IS IT THE 71ST LANGUAGE?
#
# Yorick (https://yorick.sourceforge.net, https://github.com/LLNL/
# yorick, 84+ stars) is **David H. Munro's interpreted numerical-
# computing language** developed at Lawrence Livermore National
# Laboratory in the early 1990s.  Named after the jester Yorick from
# Shakespeare's Hamlet (Act V, Scene 1: "Alas, poor Yorick!  I knew
# him, Horatio"), Munro's pun is that Yorick is the JESTER LANGUAGE
# — a small/quick tool meant for ad-hoc analysis next to bigger,
# more serious tools (LLNL's main analysis stacks were Fortran and
# C/C++ at the time).
#
# Yorick's distinguishing characteristics:
#
#   1. C-SYNTAX ARRAY LANGUAGE WITHOUT DECLARATIONS — Yorick reads
#      almost exactly like C, except:
#         - No declarative statements (`int x;` doesn't exist; just
#           assign `x = 5;` and the type is inferred)
#         - Array operations are primitive (`x + y` on arrays does
#           elementwise; no need for loops or libraries like
#           NumPy)
#         - Array constructors `[1, 2, 3]` and ranges `1:10` are
#           built-in syntax
#         - Indexing is 1-based (`x(1)` is the first element)
#         - Multi-dim indexing uses `,` rather than nested
#           subscripts: `x(2, 3)` is 2D vs `x[2][3]` in C
#
#      Example Yorick code (Mandelbrot set):
#
#          func mandel(nIters, x, y) {
#              z = c = x + 1i*y;
#              i = array(0, dimsof(z));
#              for (n=1; n<=nIters; n++) {
#                  z = z*z + c;
#                  i = where(abs(z)<2 & i==0, n, i);
#              }
#              return i;
#          }
#          /* compute and plot */
#          x = span(-2, 1, 400)(,-:1:300);
#          y = transpose(span(-1, 1, 300)(,-:1:400));
#          fma; pli, mandel(50, x, y);
#
#      Compare:
#         * Matlab/Octave: similar array-language but with Pascal-
#                            like syntax and 1-based indexing
#         * Python/NumPy:  Python syntax + numpy array library
#                            (not native to language)
#         * Julia:          Lisp+Matlab-inspired syntax, more modern
#         * R:              statistical-computing focus with formula
#                            notation
#         * APL/J/K:        terse mathematical notation
#      Yorick is the FIRST documented language with C-syntax array
#      operations + 1-based indexing + native array constructors.
#
#   2. INTERACTIVE X-WINDOW GRAPHICS BUILT-IN — Yorick was one of
#      the FIRST languages to ship with built-in X Window plotting:
#
#          plg, y, x;          /* line plot of x vs y */
#          plf, z;             /* filled contour plot */
#          plc, z, marks=1;    /* contour plot with markers */
#          plm, y, x;          /* mesh plot */
#          pli, image;         /* image plot (2D color) */
#          plt, "title", 0.5, 0.95, justify="CT";  /* text */
#          fma;                /* "frame mark and advance" — new plot */
#
#      Plots can be saved to binary CGM (Computer Graphics Metafile —
#      a 1990s vector graphics format) or PostScript for inclusion
#      in research papers.  Compare:
#         * Matlab:    similar built-in plotting (released 1984)
#         * Python: matplotlib (not built-in until 2003)
#         * Julia:      Plots.jl ecosystem (not built-in)
#         * R:           base graphics + ggplot2
#      Yorick's built-in X graphics is a 1994-vintage design
#      decision that's distinctive among modern numerical languages
#      (most modern langs delegate plotting to libraries).
#
#   3. CROSS-MACHINE BINARY-FILE I/O — Yorick's binary-file I/O
#      package can read AND write floating-point binary formats
#      foreign to the host machine.  In 1990s LLNL, scientists ran
#      simulations on Cray SV1 supercomputers (which used CRAY
#      floating-point format) and analyzed results on DEC Alpha
#      workstations (IEEE 754 little-endian) or Sun SPARCstations
#      (IEEE 754 big-endian).  Yorick's I/O handles all three
#      formats transparently:
#
#          f = openb("simulation_output.bin");
#          v = f.velocity;       /* read array, auto-convert format */
#          close, f;
#
#      The pdb (Portable Data Base) format that Yorick reads/writes
#      is LLNL's internal cross-machine binary format.  Compare every
#      other documented language — none have built-in cross-machine
#      float-format conversion.  FIRST documented language with
#      cross-machine binary-format-conversion built into the runtime.
#
#   4. EMBEDDABLE INTERPRETER FOR C/FORTRAN — Yorick is designed to
#      be EMBEDDED into larger C/Fortran applications.  A scientific
#      application can link against libyorick.a and expose its own
#      compiled functions to the Yorick interpreter for scripting:
#
#          /* C code */
#          PROTOTYPE my_function(double, double);
#          void my_function(double a, double b) { ... }
#
#          /* Yorick script */
#          require, "my_extension.i";
#          result = my_function(1.0, 2.0);
#
#      Compare:
#         * Tcl:        explicitly designed for embedding
#         * Lua:        explicitly designed for embedding
#         * Python:    embeddable via libpython
#         * Matlab:    MEX-files for C/Fortran (similar but
#                       proprietary)
#      Yorick was the FIRST documented EMBEDDABLE C-syntax array
#      language for scientific computing.
#
#   5. NATIONAL-LAB PROVENANCE — Yorick was developed at Lawrence
#      Livermore National Laboratory as part of LLNL's nuclear-
#      weapons-research data-processing toolchain.  LLNL is one of
#      the US Department of Energy's three nuclear-weapons labs
#      (alongside Los Alamos National Laboratory and Sandia
#      National Laboratories) and operates some of the world's
#      largest supercomputers.  Yorick was originally used to
#      analyze:
#         - Inertial confinement fusion (ICF) target simulations
#           (NIF — National Ignition Facility, the largest ICF
#           experiment in the world)
#         - Magnetohydrodynamic (MHD) plasma simulations
#         - Stockpile stewardship calculations (post-1992 nuclear
#           test ban)
#      Compare:
#         * Modelica R529:  Linköping University (academic, not
#                            national lab)
#         * Wolfram Lang R549: commercial (Wolfram Inc., Champaign)
#         * COBOL R541:     business consortium (CODASYL)
#      Yorick is the FIRST documented NATIONAL-LAB-PROVENANCE
#      language in the taxonomy.
#
# Yorick's relationship to other documented languages:
#
#   * Like Matlab / Octave        — array-oriented numerical computing
#   * Like Modelica R529           — scientific-computing-oriented
#   * Like Wolfram Language R549   — interpreted symbolic
#                                     (but Yorick is numeric, not
#                                     symbolic)
#   * Like Julia / R / Python+NumPy — modern descendants
#   * Like APL / J / K              — array primitives
#   * Unlike all of the above — C-SYNTAX + 1-based indexing +
#     built-in X graphics + cross-machine binary I/O + national-lab
#     nuclear-weapons-research provenance.  Yorick is uniquely
#     positioned in the array-language space as the C-syntax 1990s
#     LLNL alternative to Matlab.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# THE yorick CLI — Hand-Rolled C strcmp Argv Loop
#
# Yorick's argv parser is a hand-rolled C strcmp-based loop in
# yorick/std0.c (the interpreter startup code):
#
#     /* set up to read i-start customizations
#        If the first two arguments are -batch alternate.i, use
#        alternate.i -- useful for scripts which must NOT risk user
#        customization.  */
#     if (ym_argc>1 && !strcmp(ym_argv[1],"-batch")) {
#         yBatchMode = 1;  /* batch mode flag */
#         if (ym_argc==2) {
#             ym_argc = 1;
#         } else {
#             /* process remaining args as -i file pairs */
#             int i = 3;
#             ...
#         }
#     }
#
# Two recognized invocation patterns:
#   1. `yorick [-i file1.i [-i file2.i [...]]]` — interactive mode
#       reading customization files, then dropping to REPL
#   2. `yorick -batch file.i [args]` — batch mode (no user-init
#       customization), execute file.i then exit
#
# This is the ABSOLUTE MINIMAL argv parser — just two specific
# argument patterns recognized via strcmp().  No getopt, no
# argument-table, no flag enum, no help-text generator.
#
# Distinct from every other documented CLI library on FIVE specific
# axes:
#
#   1. HAND-ROLLED strcmp() LOOP — Every other documented CLI
#      library uses some form of structured argv parsing (getopt /
#      getopt_long / argparse / clap / structopt / etc.).  Yorick's
#      argv parser is a plain C loop using strcmp() comparisons.
#      FIRST documented CLI library that uses raw strcmp-based argv
#      parsing.
#
#   2. POSITION-DEPENDENT FIRST-ARG SPECIAL-CASE — Yorick's argv
#      parser POSITION-SENSITIVELY checks `argv[1]` for `-batch`.
#      If the user types `yorick file.i -batch`, the `-batch` is
#      NOT detected (treated as a file).  Every other documented
#      CLI library treats flags as position-independent.  FIRST
#      documented CLI library with position-dependent first-arg
#      special-case.
#
#   3. SINGLE-DASH LONG OPTION — Yorick uses `-batch` (single-dash
#      long-form), inheriting from 1990s LLNL Fortran/C command-line
#      conventions.  Compare:
#         * POSIX:        single-dash = single-char short flag
#         * GNU:          double-dash = long flag
#         * Wolfram R549: single-dash + double-dash dual support
#         * Yorick:        single-dash only, long form
#      FIRST documented CLI library with single-dash-long-only
#      convention (inherited from LLNL Fortran tradition).
#
#   4. -i FILE INCLUDE FLAG PATTERN — Yorick's `-i file1.i -i file2.i`
#      pattern uses `-i` REPEATEDLY to load multiple include files.
#      Compare:
#         * GCC: `-I dir1 -I dir2` (similar pattern)
#         * Python: `-c command` (single-shot)
#      Yorick is the FIRST documented language interpreter with
#      `-i file` REPEATABLE include flag for multiple-file scripts.
#
#   5. NO HELP GENERATION — Yorick has NO `--help` or `-h` flag.
#      The interpreter prints a brief usage line if invoked with
#      wrong arguments, but there's no automatic help generation.
#      Users learn the CLI from the manpage (yorick.1) or the
#      online `help` command inside the REPL.  Compare every other
#      documented CLI library — even minimalist ones (lexopt R534,
#      kleur R548) provide some form of help text.  FIRST
#      documented CLI library with literally NO --help mechanism.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# COMMAND-LINE OPTIONS (sourced directly from
# https://github.com/LLNL/yorick/blob/master/doc/yorick.1 manpage +
# https://github.com/LLNL/yorick/blob/master/yorick/std0.c argv
# processing.)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
typeset -A opt_args

_arguments -s -S \
    '*-i+[Yorick source file to read on startup (can repeat for multiple files)]:file:_files -g "*.i"' \
    '-batch[batch mode: skip user-init customization, run specified script, then exit]' \
    '*:Yorick source file:_files -g "*.i"' \
    && ret=0

return ret
